00:18:19,346 --> 00:18:21,107
So hi, my name is Yon.

283
00:18:22,588 --> 00:18:25,329
Um, I made a little weird presentation.

284
00:18:25,389 --> 00:18:26,070
It's an experiment.

285
00:18:26,110 --> 00:18:26,750
Please bear with me.

286
00:18:27,891 --> 00:18:30,873
Uh, welcome.

287
00:18:31,453 --> 00:18:31,513
Um,

288
00:18:37,447 --> 00:18:39,088
Please, please hold your claps.

289
00:18:40,449 --> 00:18:42,351
I'm going to be saying we a lot probably.

290
00:18:42,371 --> 00:18:44,973
It's because I have a company that's called GlitchNap.

291
00:18:45,053 --> 00:18:49,256
We're starting up a collective in Antwerp called the House of Indie, probably.

292
00:18:50,057 --> 00:18:56,342
I'm affiliated with the ITU of Copenhagen, where I'm doing, where I have started a student organization that's doing events.

293
00:18:56,843 --> 00:18:58,024
And with the Copenhagen Game Collective.

294
00:18:59,225 --> 00:19:01,846
Let me tell you the story of the last year of my life,

295
00:19:01,986 --> 00:19:04,247
because that's kind of really related to all of this.

296
00:19:04,727 --> 00:19:06,788
It all started when we made this game called Laser Knights,

297
00:19:06,908 --> 00:19:09,169
which was a four-player locomotive-player game we made

298
00:19:09,309 --> 00:19:11,690
because we didn't want to write an AI or do level design.

299
00:19:13,471 --> 00:19:13,991
We were lazy.

300
00:19:14,371 --> 00:19:17,472
So it ended up like this, where four people,

301
00:19:17,813 --> 00:19:20,074
because obviously you can't play four players on a keyboard

302
00:19:20,134 --> 00:19:21,974
because of physical space and hardware limitations,

303
00:19:22,375 --> 00:19:24,335
it ended up four people crouching in front of a computer,

304
00:19:24,415 --> 00:19:26,676
having a blast, kicking the floor, you know, jumping in the air.

305
00:19:27,237 --> 00:19:27,417
But...

306
00:19:28,989 --> 00:19:31,070
Yeah, that's not really something you can sell.

307
00:19:31,671 --> 00:19:33,072
But the interesting thing that happened here...

308
00:19:33,412 --> 00:19:36,013
This is a tilted thing. This is annoying.

309
00:19:36,794 --> 00:19:37,694
I'm just going to use a touchpad.

310
00:19:39,375 --> 00:19:39,876
Bear with me.

311
00:19:42,297 --> 00:19:46,399
So really quickly, we realized that this creates a space around your game,

312
00:19:46,459 --> 00:19:50,602
like a sort of almost physical area that you're now playing in with people.

313
00:19:52,603 --> 00:19:56,545
But it's really confining to, like, stand bent over and look at a laptop.

314
00:19:57,946 --> 00:19:58,086
So...

315
00:19:59,226 --> 00:20:03,408
What we did was we put the game in an old arcade machine, you know, like one of those old fridges,

316
00:20:03,508 --> 00:20:06,349
and we were able to, when we set it up in a public space, attract a lot of people

317
00:20:06,429 --> 00:20:09,111
because of the familiar shape of a fridge that plays video games.

318
00:20:11,123 --> 00:20:13,043
And then we were invited to the Nordic Game Indie Night

319
00:20:13,143 --> 00:20:16,184
as a nominee on the one condition, unofficially,

320
00:20:16,224 --> 00:20:18,364
the one condition that we would actually bring the arcade machine,

321
00:20:19,345 --> 00:20:21,245
which was a problem because we didn't actually own that one,

322
00:20:21,285 --> 00:20:22,145
we borrowed it from someone.

323
00:20:22,165 --> 00:20:24,866
So we decided to build our own, which led to this.

324
00:20:25,986 --> 00:20:28,307
With no money and no carpentry skills,

325
00:20:28,327 --> 00:20:31,047
we ended up buying two IKEA coffee tables,

326
00:20:31,107 --> 00:20:32,128
the cheapest ones you can get,

327
00:20:32,308 --> 00:20:34,228
and putting them together, putting a screen in there,

328
00:20:34,668 --> 00:20:37,809
and popping out four controllers, which resulted in this.

329
00:20:37,829 --> 00:20:38,789
This is my favorite picture.

330
00:20:38,849 --> 00:20:40,530
This guy is obviously having a blast.

331
00:20:41,510 --> 00:20:42,311
at playing LaserNate.

332
00:20:44,132 --> 00:20:46,514
We ended up actually winning that award,

333
00:20:46,674 --> 00:20:49,757
which I think no small part to bringing this arcade

334
00:20:49,797 --> 00:20:51,618
because we just dominated the space.

335
00:20:51,979 --> 00:20:53,140
Every game had its own booth.

336
00:20:53,180 --> 00:20:54,080
They all looked identical.

337
00:20:54,181 --> 00:20:56,883
Ours was really special because we built this physical thing.

338
00:20:58,788 --> 00:20:59,909
And it kind of went on from there.

339
00:21:00,349 --> 00:21:02,771
The problem with this one was the IKEA wood is actually cardboard,

340
00:21:02,851 --> 00:21:04,612
so the wheels we put on there kept on breaking.

341
00:21:04,972 --> 00:21:07,674
So we decided we need a new one, and let's make mobility our priority

342
00:21:07,694 --> 00:21:08,634
so we can take it everywhere.

343
00:21:08,694 --> 00:21:12,156
So we made the Babycade, which looks kind of like this.

344
00:21:15,118 --> 00:21:17,139
Again, there's a young person having a blast.

345
00:21:19,534 --> 00:21:25,318
Yeah, that's it. We couldn't get a shopping cart, so we ended up just buying the cheapest

346
00:21:25,358 --> 00:21:30,501
vintage baby stroller we could get. This has been showcased several places, and we're hoping

347
00:21:30,521 --> 00:21:36,044
to bring it to parks and just drive it around downtown with both our indie games and your

348
00:21:36,084 --> 00:21:36,944
indie games and whatever.

349
00:21:37,805 --> 00:21:42,310
A bit later, I went to Global Game Jam in Antwerp, which is my hometown, although I live in Copenhagen.

350
00:21:42,730 --> 00:21:45,693
I decided to bring part of this culture that I'm engaged with back home.

351
00:21:46,293 --> 00:21:49,537
So again, I had no money, so I bought the cheapest vintage coffee table I could find.

352
00:21:49,997 --> 00:21:54,682
I put a screen in it, and I brought it and played some of the games that I play so often in Copenhagen.

353
00:21:56,382 --> 00:22:00,184
That ended up, I ended up meeting exactly the right person who wanted to help me with this, took it forward,

354
00:22:00,224 --> 00:22:05,087
and we ended up making it into The Press X, which is a platform where we curate indie games and bring them to events.

355
00:22:05,387 --> 00:22:11,810
We've exhibited Proteus and Super Hexagon, Tengami, and other games at places that have never seen those types of games before,

356
00:22:11,990 --> 00:22:16,132
which is really awesome, and this was made in January, we finished it in February, March,

357
00:22:16,192 --> 00:22:19,154
and it's been to like ten different events, and it's gonna be hopefully more and more.

358
00:22:19,695 --> 00:22:29,375
This is a beautiful, it turned into this beautiful thing with like, we put like gold, gold plate on there that says press X and it has like gold hooks for your Xbox controllers. Really nice.

359
00:22:31,728 --> 00:22:35,451
And in this one, actually, I got invited to showcase a game at Wild Rumpus.

360
00:22:35,831 --> 00:22:38,052
And I arrived a day early, and that's a bit of a right conference.

361
00:22:38,152 --> 00:22:41,594
And I arrived a day early and I decided, well, I don't really want to see London.

362
00:22:41,994 --> 00:22:42,975
I'll just build an arcade.

363
00:22:43,255 --> 00:22:46,177
So I got somebody... I spent the whole day making phone calls.

364
00:22:46,577 --> 00:22:47,358
Again, I had no money.

365
00:22:47,978 --> 00:22:49,058
So I, um...

366
00:22:50,179 --> 00:22:56,924
I got somebody to lug these pallets through downtown London with me on foot, like a kilometer

367
00:22:56,944 --> 00:23:01,668
or two, and ended up at the venue and just cut a hole in the top, put a screen in there,

368
00:23:01,748 --> 00:23:06,112
and again, I made this thing with very little effort that just completely dominated the

369
00:23:06,632 --> 00:23:09,014
space at the Bit of Alright conference and at Wild Rumpus.

370
00:23:10,895 --> 00:23:13,017
So, to sum up, what I'm trying to say is,

371
00:23:13,577 --> 00:23:16,239
build arcades, it works out, it's great,

372
00:23:16,359 --> 00:23:17,960
it's great fun and it's really rewarding.

373
00:23:19,240 --> 00:23:21,662
Use whatever you can find, bring them wherever you go,

374
00:23:21,902 --> 00:23:23,223
and organize meetings for them.

375
00:23:23,823 --> 00:23:26,845
Basically, if you build them, if you build it, they will come.

376
00:23:29,167 --> 00:23:33,828
So I wish I could tell you that I have some master plan where a year ago I decided to become a game installation artist.

377
00:23:34,948 --> 00:23:39,810
I wish I could tell you it was super easy getting these projects funded and finding materials, etc. etc.

378
00:23:40,110 --> 00:23:43,391
I wish I could tell you there's never been any hammering or gluing or sawing mistakes.

379
00:23:45,435 --> 00:23:48,978
I can't, but I can guarantee that these machines are a really good way to get your game to

380
00:23:49,038 --> 00:23:53,261
actually be played by people you otherwise have a difficult time reaching, because they

381
00:23:53,281 --> 00:23:58,084
don't necessarily understand computers, but they understand the shape of whatever it is

382
00:23:58,124 --> 00:24:00,786
you have there, or they understand that this is something interesting that they should

383
00:24:00,806 --> 00:24:01,366
pay attention to.

384
00:24:02,067 --> 00:24:06,149
It can also get you invited to a lot of cool parties, like GDC Europe.

385
00:24:09,454 --> 00:24:11,055
In our case, it won us our first award.

386
00:24:11,075 --> 00:24:14,457
I got here to come to GDC Europe and sort of host a panel.

387
00:24:15,938 --> 00:24:17,419
I really recommend it.

388
00:24:17,679 --> 00:24:21,061
The thing we started in Antwerp, I put a screen in a coffee table

389
00:24:21,201 --> 00:24:24,123
and since then we've curated two entire exhibitions

390
00:24:24,463 --> 00:24:26,304
and we've brought it to ten other events.

391
00:24:28,745 --> 00:24:31,907
So, to round us all off, I have no idea how I am on time.

392
00:24:35,576 --> 00:24:40,277
Why I think this matters from a sort of higher point of view,

393
00:24:41,358 --> 00:24:44,999
these devices are the only gateway, or every device is a gateway

394
00:24:45,039 --> 00:24:46,560
to the digital world inside.

395
00:24:46,740 --> 00:24:48,600
If you want any game to be played by humans,

396
00:24:48,640 --> 00:24:51,721
you have to make an interface to the physical world,

397
00:24:53,582 --> 00:24:55,163
which means you're giving it a physical shape.

398
00:24:55,443 --> 00:24:57,903
You don't do this consciously when you make a computer game

399
00:24:57,943 --> 00:25:00,544
because the computer is your shape, but you totally have the power

400
00:25:00,604 --> 00:25:02,965
to put it in any other shape, and every shape is different.

401
00:25:05,762 --> 00:25:08,406
Using shapes that we're familiar with has really interesting consequences.

402
00:25:08,486 --> 00:25:11,691
The three crates, pallets I put on top of each other were so sturdy,

403
00:25:12,012 --> 00:25:13,935
people were standing on them and dancing and sitting,

404
00:25:14,075 --> 00:25:17,500
and it was so makeshift, I was just going to trash it, I wasn't going to bring it back home.

405
00:25:17,846 --> 00:25:22,327
I handed out markers and duct tape for people to tag it and make it, you know, this sort

406
00:25:22,367 --> 00:25:24,968
of old, you know, here today, gone tomorrow thing.

407
00:25:26,148 --> 00:25:29,849
The Press X, on the other hand, became this beautiful ornament, like we ended up lacking

408
00:25:29,909 --> 00:25:34,491
it so it's shiny and it's beautiful and people just want to go in there and be enthralled

409
00:25:34,551 --> 00:25:37,571
in whatever magical, beautiful indie game we put on there.

410
00:25:40,732 --> 00:25:46,074
So and to connect it to the other things, events and showcases is where these installations

411
00:25:46,114 --> 00:25:46,754
come to fruition.

412
00:25:47,877 --> 00:25:53,019
The importance of local multiplayer games has been argued quite a lot in last year's, you know,

413
00:25:53,039 --> 00:25:54,699
Dispatch Friends, Kickstarter, and stuff like that.

414
00:25:55,160 --> 00:25:59,741
These events, they can provide the critical mass that those games need to make sense,

415
00:26:00,081 --> 00:26:01,582
both for players and spectators.

416
00:26:02,162 --> 00:26:06,563
Games like that often don't make any sense when you just play them like a four-player game

417
00:26:06,583 --> 00:26:08,444
with only three people and there's no spectators.

418
00:26:08,504 --> 00:26:10,044
That's not the same.

419
00:26:12,145 --> 00:26:17,427
To me, they are to games what movie nights are to movies, or concerts are to music.

420
00:26:18,425 --> 00:26:21,892
It's a place where you come and you enjoy the games that are being curated or that you

421
00:26:21,912 --> 00:26:23,515
brought yourself with your friends.

422
00:26:27,364 --> 00:26:32,466
Then also at these events, interesting things happen where these

423
00:26:33,027 --> 00:26:34,567
concerts or movie nights overlap.

424
00:26:34,627 --> 00:26:37,649
This is Chipsle playing at the Wild Rampus party in front of Super

425
00:26:37,669 --> 00:26:42,892
Hexagon, which is a super interesting combination of two forms of media.

426
00:26:43,932 --> 00:26:47,634
Same thing happened to the game I made Go Nuts, and DJ's wearing

427
00:26:47,714 --> 00:26:51,616
robot masks while we're trying to play it on his body.

428
00:26:52,317 --> 00:26:55,298
And that's all I have to say.

429
00:26:57,412 --> 00:27:01,814
I hope you are inspired to start doing the same thing I have so I can bring my arcades

430
00:27:01,874 --> 00:27:02,494
to your parties.

431
00:27:04,535 --> 00:27:06,076
Thanks a lot for listening, thanks for coming.

